{"timestamp":"2026-05-28T08:11:56.335Z","type":"tool","step":"IDLE","details":{"toolName":"task","args":{"description":"Analyze UX gaps","prompt":"Research-only task. Do not edit files.\n\nInitiative: Align Implementation with Philosophy\nObjective: Analyze the gap between the current opencode-mdocs implementation and the project's philosophy, then produce a roadmap improving both product/UX behavior and technical architecture for shared durable memory for a distributed single agent.\n\nRelevant philosophy summary:\n- AI agent instances in different terminals/apps/machines are facets of one distributed entity.\n- The system needs shared, durable memory accessible to every instance.\n- Memory has two layers: Initiatives = practical collaborative workflow state; Wiki = stable long-term agent-managed knowledge.\n- Humans deserve readable/shareable/referenceable access, while agents deserve memory organized for their reasoning.\n\nCurrent plan step: Identify product/UX behavior gaps.\nScope:\n1. Read README Philosophy, mdocs/wiki/philosophy/core-principles.md, origin-narrative.md.\n2. Inspect README workflow/tool sections and agents/mdocs-orchestrator.md/skills for how users and agents are guided.\n3. Identify product/UX gaps: onboarding, initiative discovery/resume, handoff continuity, wiki discoverability, agent autonomy, human readability, friction, failure recovery, and multi-agent experience.\n4. Return prioritized improvement opportunities with rough phase suggestions.\n\nVerification criteria: Findings should map back to the three philosophy principles and cite relevant files/sections. Return only a concise structured report; no code changes.","subagent_type":"explore","task_id":"","command":"analyze philosophy UX gaps"}}}
{"timestamp":"2026-05-28T08:12:00.562Z","type":"tool","step":"IDLE","details":{"toolName":"task","args":{"description":"Analyze architecture gaps","prompt":"Research-only task. Do not edit files.\n\nInitiative: Align Implementation with Philosophy\nObjective: Analyze the gap between the current opencode-mdocs implementation and the project's philosophy, then produce a roadmap improving both product/UX behavior and technical architecture for shared durable memory for a distributed single agent.\n\nRelevant philosophy summary:\n- AI agent instances in different terminals/apps/machines are facets of one distributed entity.\n- The system needs shared, durable memory accessible to every instance.\n- Memory has two layers: Initiatives = practical collaborative workflow state; Wiki = stable long-term agent-managed knowledge.\n- Humans deserve readable/shareable/referenceable access, while agents deserve memory organized for their reasoning.\n\nCurrent plan step: Identify technical architecture gaps.\nScope:\n1. Inspect src/plugin.ts, src/workflow.ts, src/initiative.ts, src/wiki.ts, src/subagent.ts, src/search.ts, src/audit.ts, src/linter.ts, and tests.\n2. Compare implementation to philosophy and original architecture docs in mdocs/wiki/architecture/.\n3. Identify technical gaps around persistence, workflow state, context assembly, indexing/search, cross-linking, concurrency/multi-agent safety, extensibility, custom tools, and durable memory semantics.\n4. Return prioritized improvement opportunities with rough phase suggestions.\n\nVerification criteria: Findings should map back to the three philosophy principles and cite relevant files/classes/functions. Return only a concise structured report; no code changes.","subagent_type":"explore","task_id":"","command":"analyze architecture gaps"}}}
{"timestamp":"2026-05-28T08:12:56.792Z","type":"tool","step":"IDLE","details":{"toolName":"task","args":{"description":"Analyze memory model","prompt":"Research-only task. Do not edit files.\n\nInitiative: Align Implementation with Philosophy\nObjective: Analyze the gap between the current opencode-mdocs implementation and the project's philosophy, then produce a roadmap improving both product/UX behavior and technical architecture for shared durable memory for a distributed single agent.\n\nRelevant philosophy summary:\n- AI agent instances in different terminals/apps/machines are facets of one distributed entity.\n- The system needs shared, durable memory accessible to every instance.\n- Memory has two layers: Initiatives = practical collaborative workflow state; Wiki = stable long-term agent-managed knowledge.\n- Humans deserve readable/shareable/referenceable access, while agents deserve memory organized for their reasoning.\n\nCurrent plan step: Analyze knowledge model and agent autonomy.\nScope:\n1. Inspect initiative/wiki templates, managers, linter, search, dispatch assembly, README docs, and mdocs wiki/initiative examples.\n2. Identify gaps in the initiatives/wiki boundary, metadata, cross-linking, lifecycle, wiki organization freedom, human-readable views, derived knowledge, and memory compaction/summarization.\n3. Look for places where the current system is too human-documentation-like or too workflow-only versus agent-owned memory.\n4. Return prioritized improvement opportunities with rough phase suggestions.\n\nVerification criteria: Findings should map back to the two-layer memory philosophy and cite relevant files/sections. Return only a concise structured report; no code changes.","subagent_type":"explore","task_id":"","command":"analyze memory model gaps"}}}
